Incident.Summary: Four vehicle collision on Maryland RT 2 at Skinner's Turn Road. The driver of vehicle 1 showed signs of impairment, performed poorly on SFST's, and was arrested for DUI. Arrestee submitted to a blood-kit and an Emergency Petition was completed.

IncidentSuppNarrative.NarrativeText:
This stop was audibly and visually recorded using the Axon Digital Video System installed in Maryland State Police Vehicle, U-40, as well as my Axon body worn camera.
 

  •    Defendant: Mark Scott Hurley.
  •    Date of Birth: 03/21/1991
  •    Date of Arrest: 11/11/2023
  •    Time of Arrest: 1734 hours  
  •    DUI# 23-098 (Prince Frederick) 

CERTIFICATE AND TRAINING: 
  •     Trained in administering Standardized Field Sobriety Tests through the Maryland State Police and National Highway Safety Administration. 


VEHICLE IN MOTION (PHASE 1) 

 On November 11, 2023, at approximately 1408 hours, I, Tpr E. Barrientos #7396 was on uniformed patrol in my marked Maryland State Police vehicle, U-40, when I responded to the area of Maryland Route 2 and Skinners Turn Road, Owings, Calvert County, Maryland for the report of a vehicle collision involving injuries. 

I arrived on scene at approximately 1411 hours, where I made contact with multiple parties involved. I observed four vehicles to be involved in the collision and began to make contact with the parties involved. I requested Emergency Medical Services (EMS) to respond to the scene of the collision upon observing multiple injured parties.

I identified the following vehicles to be involved in the collision:

Vehicle 1: Green 1996 Ford Explorer bearing MD 6Z4271, operated by Mark Scott Hurley (W/M DOB: 03/21/1991)
Vehicle 2: Silver 2020 Nissan Rogue bearing MD 3FE1942, operated by Coleene McBryde (B/F DOB: 03/19/1951)
Vehicle 3: Gray 2022 Acura MDX bearing MD 1AK5832, operated by Brett Timothy Boucher (W/M DOB 06/20/1983); Front seat passenger - Amy Roberts Boucher (W/F DOB 06/09/1984); Right rear passenger - Tunya Moore Taylor (B/F DOB: 10/05/1967)
Vehicle 4: Blue 2014 Toyota Scion bearing MD 7FF7278, operated by Daniil James Byram (W/M DOB: 09/05/2005); Front passenger - Hunter Zeke Boswell (W/M DOB: 10/27/2005); Right rear passenger - Carly Rae Hart (W/F DOB: 05/07/2007)

The following witnesses were identified: 
Witness #1: Mark Jeffrey Morgan (B/M DOB: 11/17/1975)
Witness #2: Erin Rae Whipkey (W/F DOB: 02/03/1984)

    Upon briefly interviewing the witnesses, both Whipkey and Morgan advised that the driver of vehicle 1, Hurley, was swerving while driving northbound on MD Route 2. Whipkey stated that Hurley was “swerving all over the road miles back.” Morgan stated that Hurley was “swerving two miles back”, and also advised that vehicle 2 was slowing down due to traffic when Hurley failed to slow down to avoid colliding with vehicle 2. Morgan also stated in a written statement, that Hurley "appeared to be on some substance when getting out of the car." Cpl. Shrawder #6043 with the Calvert County Sheriff’s Office, stated that when speaking with Hurley, Hurley advised Cpl. Shrawder that he was traveling southbound on MD Route 2 at Skinners Turn Road behind vehicle 2, where he then stated he rear ended vehicle 2.

    Whipkey provided video footage of the collision and of the Hurley's driving behavior prior to the collision that was recorded on her personal dash cam. In the video's provided, I observed Hurley driving northbound MD Route 2 swerving in and out of his lane and also observed Hurley driving on the right-side shoulder for extended periods of time and then returning to his lane. Hurley was also captured crossing the solid white line of the right turn lane towards Dalrymple Road by half of his vehicle, then returning to the northbound Lane after the right turn lane ends. The witness statements that were taken align with the provided video footage. According to a witness statement taken from the driver of vehicle 4, Byram, when Byram checked on Hurley's well-being, Hurley stated to Byram that he was on his cellphone looking at his Global Positioning System (GPS), and that the collision happened due to vehicle 2 not using a turn signal. Hurley did not mention using his cellphone when I interviewed him. 

    I observed the driver of vehicle 2, McBryde, be treated and transported to University of Maryland Capital Region Medical Center by Calvert County EMS (Run # 1857) before being interviewed. I observed minor scratches on the left arm of Brett Boucher, but he advised that he did not need medical services. I observed Hurley with injuries to his mouth and right leg, but he refused further medical treatment when offered at the scene. All the other parties refused medical treatment. 



PERSONAL CONTACT (PHASE 2) 

    Hurley provided a copy of his DR-15(a) that he was provided on a prior arrest for Driving While Impaired. I observed Hurley to be in a disoriented state, speaking in a lethargic manner, off balanced, and would repeat his statements. While using his cellphone, Hurley was unable to maintain a straight posture, and began to shift his body weight to his right hip while slightly bending his knees. Hurley was evaluated by EMS on scene. The EMS personnel did not state that Hurley had suffered a head injury, and also advised that Hurley was refusing further medical care. When asking Hurley if he was okay, Hurley stated yes and also stated "that guy (McBryde) was not using his turn signal, not using his turn signal, and when I turned left... well... yea... I, yea." Hurley stated that the reason for the collision was due to vehicle 2 not using a turn signal. Hurley advised that he was traveling northbound on MD Route 2 heading to Annapolis, MD when the collision occurred.


PRE-ARREST SCREENING (PHASE 3)

Based on my observations, I asked Hurley to perform Standardized Field Sobriety Test's (SFST's).

    I asked Hurley to stand with his feet together and to place his hands at his sides. Hurley advised that he had not taken any medication, and that he did not wear glasses. Hurley stated that he had his retina scratched in the past, and had sustained injuries to his right leg during the collision. Hurley stated that he did not feel comfortable completing the Walk and Turn and One Leg Stand test portion of the SFST's. The SFST was completed on the shoulder of the northbound side of MD Route 2 where it was flat, level, and free of debris. The weather was clear. The SFST were performed with the following results:

HORIZONTAL GAZE NYSTAGMUS (HGN): (6/6)

Hurley was instructed to stand with his feet together and to place his hands at his sides. Hurley was instructed to hold his head still, and to follow the stimulus with his eyes and his eyes only. Placing my stimulus 12 - 15 inches away from Hurley, I then checked his eyes for equal pupil size, equal tracking, and resting nystagmus. This is done to identify a possible medical condition that may exhibit resting nystagmus. I observed none of these in Hurley's eyes. 

1. Hurley displayed a lack of smooth pursuit in both eyes.
2. Hurley displayed distinct and sustained nystagmus at maximum deviation in both eyes.
3. Hurley displayed the on-set of nystagmus prior to forty-five degrees in both eyes.

Hurley had to be reminded to follow the stimulus with his eyes, as he would stop following it to speak to me.

WALK AND TURN: (0/8)

Hurley advised that he did not feel comfortable completing the Walk and Turn due to leg injuries sustained during the collision. The test was not completed.

ONE LEG STAND TEST: (0/4)

Hurley advised that he did not feel comfortable completing the One Leg Stand test due to leg injuries sustained during the collision. The test was not completed.

PRELIMINARY BREATH TEST:
Hurley was offered the Preliminary Breath Test (PBT), which resulted in 0.00 BrAC. 

ARREST:  
  At approximately 1459 hours, Hurley was arrested for Driving While Impaired by a Controlled Dangerous Substance (CDS). Hurley was transported to the Prince Frederick barrack at approximately 1528 hours after being medically cleared and refusing medical care at the scene of the collision. At the barrack, Hurley requested EMS due to more pain emitting from the injuries sustained during the collision. Prior to being transported to CalvertHealth Medical Center, I consulted with TFC Backus #6648, who is a Drug Recognition Expert (DRE), and he recommended that I offer Hurley a blood kit at the hospital. At approximately 1550 hours, Hurley was transported to CalvertHealth Medical Center for further medical care. At approximately 1605 hours, Hurley was provided a paper copy and was read his Advice of Rights (DR-15) without interruption. It should be noted that when being read his Advice of Rights, Hurley was unable to maintain a steady level of attention and displayed cyclic behavior. Hurley would close his eyes for an extended period of time and then would display blank stares with droopy eyes.
 
    Hurley continued to display a lethargic physical state when interacting with the medical staff. At the hospital, Hurley stated "I'm manic bipolar and I don't know what's real right now. Like is this real?" Hurley was given the opportunity to talk to his lawyer via cellphone on multiple attempts as he requested legal advice regarding the DR-15. Hurley was able to communicate with his attorney after screening with the law firm clerk, and spoke with his attorney via phone call for approximately 5 minutes. Hurley stated that he was diagnosed with Anxiety and Bipolar medical disorder, and was prescribed multiple medication for them. Hurley also stated that he suffered from Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder and a reading comprehension disorder, but was not confirmed to be diagnosed. Hurley would often mumble his words, and speak to himself. Hurley would advise the medical staff of the details from the collision, and at one point he had stated that he was one hundred yards away from the vehicle in front of him. Hurley would change the distance, later on saying he was fifty yards away. Hurley also stated several times that he "dislocated" his right bicep. An X-Ray was completed on Hurley, and it revealed that Hurley did not break any bones during the collision. A Computed Tomography (CT) scan was conducted on Hurley, to which medical staff did not observe any issues.

    At approximately 1734 hours, Hurley agreed to submit to an Evidentiary Blood Test. At approximately 1812 hours, Jasmine King with the CalvertHealth Medical Center, completed the blood draw obtaining the blood specimen.

    Hurley continued to exhibit cyclic behavior. Hurley would often close his eyes, lay back in the bed in silence, and then would rise in energy level stating that he was manic and was "freaking out." Hurley continued to exhibit blank stares when spoken to. Hurley would also cover his face from the ceiling light using his hoodie, and begin to mumble his words speaking to himself repeating some details of the collision and stated that it was the fault of vehicle 2 not using a turn signal.

Hurley was asked about his current state, and was asked if he ever thought of harming himself, to which Hurley nodded yes. Hurley was then asked when the last time he thought about harming himself was, to which he replied "the other day and now." Hurley was then asked if he was thinking about harming himself right now, to which Hurley replied "Yea."

At approximately 1840 hours, paperwork for an Emergency Petition for Hurley was completed. Hurley remained under the care of the CalvertHealth Medical Center.

Hurley was given a copy of the DR-15 form. 

The ACRS was completed in Delta Plus pending citations.

I request this case remain open pending results of the blood-kit.

All events occurred in Calvert County, MD.
